        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@justinmk If the hardcoded patterns should be preserved, even if not in sync with `files.watcherExclude` from vscode, some of the steps below could mitigate the problem:\r\n\r\n- Pass the `client` (or `client.id`) to the custom \"watch\" implementation, via `vim._watch.watch.Opts`, so when monkey patching `_watchfunc`, `vim._watch.watch.Opts.exclude_pattern` can be selectively overwritten. `client` is already used in the `callback` function.\r\n- Provide a few more useful values to the custom \"watch\" implementation, like the original glob patterns of the received `FileSystemWatcher`s, so they can be filtered or deduplicated, with the result of spawning less watchers. That could be done again via `vim._watch.watch.Opts`, by providing the original glob patterns corresponding to the already provided `include_pattern` option.\r\n- Use two different hardcoded patterns instead of the single `_poll_exclude_pattern`. One for excluding notifications of changed files and another for excluding directories to watch (e.g. for the `watchdirs` watcher). And allow to overwrite both.\r\n- Make it clear that the \"watch\" handler can be overwritten (like `vim.notify`) by making the `vim.lsp._watchfiles` module public and maybe also making it available via the global `vim.lsp` table.\r\n\r\n",
